<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-209-078 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 649 910</DOCID><JOURNAL>CVGIP: Image Understanding  March 1991 v53 n2 p211(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Note: On active contour models and balloons. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cohen, Laurent D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Snakes, or energy-minimizing curves, are used to extract featuresof interest in images.andP;  A model of deformation is presented thatsolves problems in the original method introduced by Kass, Witkinand Terzopoulos.andP;  More stable results are produced by modifyingthe external forces that push the curve to the edges.andP;  Theoriginal snake is not attracted to the contours when it is notclose enough to them and straightens to a line.andP;  This model makesthe curve behave like a balloon inflated by an additional force.andO;The initial curve no longer needs to be close to the solution toconverge; it passes over weak edges and is stopped only if theedge is strong.andP;  A first step toward three-dimensional objectreconstruction is made by tracking the extracted contour on aseries of successive cross sections.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image ProcessingTheoretical ResearchCurve FittingModelingThree-Dimensional GraphicsFeature MeasurementNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Instability due to time discretization. (chart)Instability due to space discretization. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>